AI

Accelerating Intelligence: How Startups are Revamping the AI Stack

Andrew Dyer

Jan 22, 2025 ⋅  16 min read

Key Insights

  • Accelerator rounds in crypto and AI provide not just early capital but also domain-specific support that catapults high-potential projects into subsequent large-scale raises and TGEs.
  • Data bottlenecks remain paramount for next-gen AI models, driving novel token-incentivized approaches to collection, labeling, and storage.
  • Distributed training solutions highlight a possible shift toward genuinely decentralized large-scale model development.
  • Emerging post-training and inference platforms underscore the need for more affordable, flexible solutions to refine and serve AI at scale.
  • Accelerator participants are also focusing heavily on consumer apps for content creation, as well as agents for process automation.

Accelerator programs provide start-ups and protocols with capital, mentorship, and networks of domain experts in order to find better product-market-fit. These programs are often early to supporting future heavy-weights in their respective categories. For example, protocols funded by accelerators like CSX, Beacon Accelerator, Orange DAO, Alliance DAO, and Binance Labs have either gone on to do large follow-on rounds or even TGE at very high valuations. Glow, a DePIN solar protocol, participated in Alliance DAO’s program in mid-2023 and then went on to raise $30 million from Framework and USV. Nillion, an infrastructure network focused on private computation, was backed by Beacon Accelerator and later did a $25 million follow-on round, with mainnet launching in February. Similarly, Babylon, a BTC staking protocol, started with an accelerator investment from the Interchain Foundation in 2023, and is now backed by major players like Polychain and Paradigm.

This piece will be focusing on 2024 accelerator rounds in the AI sector and the problems these protocols and companies are trying to solve. We will discuss recent changes in the AI landscape, constraints companies and developers are facing, and how crypto rails may play a role in mitigating them. We will look at where accelerator programs are investing, how these investments compare to some current offerings in the market, and if there are any new angles or opportunities for these protocols going forward.

Primer on the AI Model Development Workflow

Creating a high-performant LLM is an expansive, iterative, and expensive process. Researchers at companies like OpenAI and Anthropic are constantly developing new techniques to scale and squeeze out more model performance at each step in the process. The major parts of the workflow are as follows:

  • Data collection + pre-processing: companies will scrape most of the internet for high-quality, human-generated textual data. Pre-processing involves data cleaning, quality control, and extensive filtering. Companies will also partner with private companies that have unique datasets (like Reddit) or scrape multi-modal data (video, audio, other media) to improve their models.
  • Training: the goal of the initial phase of training is to create a model around a large, general-purpose dataset to learn broad patterns and structures in language in an unsupervised manner. This is generally the most computationally demanding part of the flow that requires large clusters of GPUs and massive amounts of energy.
  • Post-training: this involves further refinement and optimization of the model through narrow, specialized datasets. Post-training techniques include reinforcement learning from human feedback (RLHF), pruning, preference fine-tuning, and others. Synthetic data generation may be used to help models refine their knowledge and address certain gaps in training datasets.
  • Inference: this is when the models are pinged with an input (prompt) and requesting an output. While top of the line GPUs are required for the training phase, older hardware can still be used effectively for inference. Researchers have found they can scale performance of models at the time of inference through “chain-of-thought” reasoning that models like o3 use.

Perhaps just a few years ago, researchers believed model performance could mainly only be improved in the training phase. Scaling through model size (number of parameters) requires not only multiples more computation and energy, but also data. This constraint has been partially ameliorated by new techniques in other parts of the workflow that improve performance (like data curation or RLHF techniques). Given this background, where might crypto protocols and companies have the opportunity to solve problems across this stack?

Data Collection + Storage

AI companies are quickly approaching a point where the internet’s accessible and useful data is almost exhausted. Concept frequency within datasets and model performance are shown to have a log-linear relationship - this implies that we will need exponentially more data to get linear improvements in performance. The current estimate for when we might run out of high-quality data on the internet is around 2028 (although the initial estimate was moved out with advancements in certain techniques). Data is unequivocally a major future bottleneck for better models; we simply need more of it.

Alliance DAO-backed Datahive is one such protocol trying to provide major value on the data front by using token incentives. Users can download a chrome extension that runs in the background, using a portion of one’s bandwidth to scrape the public internet in exchange for rewards. One common misconception is that these types of extensions are some form of malware, but the data collection is entirely separate from a user’s web surfing and does not collect browsing history, inputs, or logins.

Datahive is a direct competitor with Grass, which has recently reached some major milestones using a similar collection model. Grass is looking to eventually switch away from its chrome extension towards desktop nodes. Their recent “Scion” network upgrade led to 60x efficiency in data retrieval, massively increasing the network’s scraping capacity. Grass also hopes to implement multi-modal search in the future, so that models can search for insights across audio, video, and text at once. This initiative would be extremely valuable pre-processing provided to the model development flow.

Instead of passive scraping through users’ browsers, CSX-backed Valyu Network created an exchange which connects data providers to AI model creators. Users with unique or specialized datasets can monetize and license their data, while model creators can easily search, filter, and compare datasets for their needs. Valyu has a system for scoring datasets for the quality of documentation, freshness, and trustworthiness, which is an important feature for model creators who need to ruthlessly filter out low-quality data. Users can also enhance their supplied datasets with synthetic data easily on the platform.

Meanwhile, Beacon Accelerator-backed Fraction AI takes a slightly different approach. One part of the platform gives token rewards for dataset contributions - either submissions (images, text, audio, etc.), data labeling, or data quality verification. The other part of the platform implements “data competitions.” Builders can deploy an agent that is tasked with generating high-quality synthetic data, which is then compared with the output from other competing agents. Builders whose agents perform better get larger token rewards, all while the platform generates a continuous stream of high-quality training data for models. It’s possible this adversarial setup and the incentives involved generate unique or better quality synthetic data than could be obtained otherwise.

Storage

Vast amounts of storage and memory are required at every step of the flow. Raw data and preprocessed data must be stored. Training requires storing checkpoints and intermediate results through iterative training runs. Models themselves must be stored in accessible repositories for deployment, and then real-time inference generates outputs that may be logged for feedback. As AI workloads increase, storage requirements grow exponentially in data centers; they will similarly grow at the edge for IoT devices where local storage becomes necessary.

It’s highly unlikely that hyperscalers and large model developers will suddenly opt for crypto-based storage solutions, given they develop in-house solutions or partner with specialized providers (like DDN or Pure Storage). But smaller companies, independent researchers, and individual AI-enabled app developers may greatly benefit from the cost-effectiveness and speed of certain crypto solutions.

Alliance DAO–backed 0G is positioning itself as a data availability and storage solution specifically designed for AI workloads. Rather than relying on a single centralized provider, 0G spreads data across a global network of nodes, each incentivized to store and serve data with speed, security, and cryptographic verification. This approach not only reduces the risk of single points of failure but also creates a marketplace where developers can benefit from lower costs, transparent pricing, and potentially more flexible storage options than traditional cloud giants.

In practice, smaller AI-focused teams—those who can’t afford to manage full-blown data centers or pay high enterprise fees—might tap into 0G’s network for more cost-effective storage and other services through their ecosystem partners. Given that onchain computation is usually prohibitively expensive, 0G also provides verifiable inference through privacy-preserving methods like zkML to ensure that offchain computations are valid.

Some potential benefits of 0G’s decentralized approach (and other protocols providing these services in this manner) include:

  • Redundancy & Reliability: Data is stored across many nodes, reducing risks from regional outages.
  • Transparent, Market-Driven Pricing: Token incentives can create competitive costs for storage and compute.
  • Tamper-Proof Data Integrity: Cryptographic proofs protect against unauthorized modifications or data poisoning.
  • Open Collaboration: Independent researchers and smaller companies can more easily share or monetize datasets and models.

0G’s infrastructure will also support the ongoing proliferation of onchain agents and agentic apps. The protocol can provide secure access to on-chain datasets and compute resources through its network partners like Talus and Theoriq. It can also obviously provide storage systems for permanent storage of agent metadata - its architecture already supports Eliza agents for: verifiable inference, agent model fine-tuning, file sharing, and more.

Training + Compute

On the compute front, new GPU-as-a-service platforms like Kaisar Network (Outlier Ventures) are still being launched. Additionally, Compute Labs (Beacon Accelerator) is pioneering “AI-Fi,” or making compute assets like NVIDIA H200’s investable on a fractionalized basis for the average investor. But we think there is probably more potential in distributed training versus any additional efforts in standard compute networks or financialization in this manner.

EXO Labs (Beacon Accelerator) is developing a system for running large language models across multiple devices using pipeline-parallel inference. This technique splits an LLM into “shards”—contiguous sets of layers—placed on GPUs in separate machines. Although this can slightly slow down performance for a single request due to network hops, the real benefit appears when multiple requests arrive concurrently: once the first shard passes activations to the second shard, the first shard is immediately freed up to handle a new request, leading to high overall throughput. This design makes it possible to host models on otherwise insufficient hardware clusters (for instance, multiple MacBook Pros networked together) and significantly boosts batch or parallel workloads.

Beyond inference, EXO contributes to distributed training by experimenting with techniques like DiLoCo (Distributed Low-Communication). Their SPARTA method can cut synchronization costs by factors of 100 to 1,000, making it feasible to train models over slower, more widely dispersed connections—such as basic internet setups. EXO’s “Gym” simulation environment allows rapid testing of these approaches under different conditions, so researchers can fine-tune parameters (like how often to synchronize or how many model weights to exchange) before deploying at scale. By focusing on both pipeline parallelism (primarily for inference) and low-communication methods (for training), EXO aims to orchestrate high-performance AI workflows on commodity hardware that might otherwise be off-limits for large-scale model development.

Meanwhile, outside of Accelerator rounds, Prime Intellect specializes in managing large-scale distributed training runs across unpredictable, globally scattered GPU nodes. Their PRIME framework, alongside approaches like DiLoCo, demonstrates that frontier-sized language models can be trained even in low-bandwidth, fault-prone environments. Taken together, EXO’s orchestration of hardware clusters and Prime Intellect’s resilient training methods signal a shift toward truly decentralized AI: one in which smaller labs, or even individual contributors, can pool their resources, lower costs, and keep pace with proprietary, data-center-driven advancements.

Post-training

DeepSeek’s (a Chinese AI company founded in 2023) latest research illustrates a novel way to boost a language model’s reasoning abilities purely through reinforcement learning (RL)—even without the usual supervised fine-tuning (SFT). Starting from a base model, their pipeline incrementally shapes chain-of-thought (CoT) logic through targeted RL rewards for correct answers and well-structured reasoning. Eventually, the DeepSeek-R1 checkpoint exhibits state-of-the-art results in math, code, and knowledge tasks, rivaling well-known closed-source models. This success story demonstrates how innovative post-training strategies—beyond the conventional pre-training plus small SFT approach—can push open-source AI to exciting new levels of performance.

While accelerator cohorts often include AI infrastructure projects—such as GPU spot marketplaces or model repositories—comparatively fewer protocols concentrate specifically on post-training tasks like reinforcement learning, reward modeling, or alignment. Most investments still gravitate toward solving bigger bottlenecks (e.g., data acquisition, training compute, or inference). Post-training, which includes RL tuning, data curation, and iterative model refinement, often remains underfunded. DeepSeek’s breakthrough thus highlights the possibility that more attention here could yield major improvements for open models.

The primary fine-tuning offering in the market is through Bittensor’s Subnet 37. This subnet allows participants to train specialized models on top of already pre-trained ones. By pulling data from other subnets—like SN18 for synthetic datasets and SN9 for foundational models—Subnet 37 closes the loop on Bittensor’s end-to-end AI pipeline. Participants fine-tune models locally, publish them to private Hugging Face repositories, and then validators automatically download and evaluate them, awarding tokens to the top-performing model. Over time, this approach builds a growing catalog of specialized open-source models, fully integrated with the rest of the Bittensor ecosystem.

There may be other opportunities for protocols in this phase of model development. For instance:

  • A community might collectively manage and fund large-scale RL tasks, paying out bounties for correct or high-quality chain-of-thought contributions.
  • A tokenized reward system could also reward adversarial “red teamers” who systematically probe the model for logical flaws, helping refine reward models in a decentralized way.
  • A DAO might organize model merging or “checkpoint governance” in a more transparent and trust-minimized fashion, collectively choosing which RL-updated checkpoint meets standards for public release.

These approaches inject open, community-driven improvements into post-training—potentially accelerating breakthroughs like the ones we’ve seen with DeepSeek.

Inference

Over the last year, a growing consensus has formed that most AI-related compute demand will shift dramatically from training toward inference. Whereas historically up to 95% of AI compute was allocated to large-scale training runs and only 5% used to serve model inferences, this ratio appears to be leveling out and will soon tip heavily in favor of inference. Once a model is pre-trained, it needs frequent and ongoing inference cycles—from powering chatbots and real-time data extraction pipelines to generating synthetic data for continual model improvement. In short, the operational workload to “serve” models is quickly overtaking the more occasional workload of creating them in the first place.

Against this backdrop, new protocols and services have emerged to address the growing appetite for affordable, on-demand inference. One clear opportunity lies in leveraging underutilized GPU capacity. As Sam Hogan, founder of Kuzco, emphasized in a recent conversation, data centers typically run at high nominal utilization but still waste significant idle GPU cycles—often five to ten percent of capacity each month. Rather than buying entire, expensive clusters, developers can tap a spot market for inference, matching their workloads to pockets of unused compute. This approach can drastically lower costs and expand access to smaller players who cannot pay premium rates at centralized providers.

Notably, the hardware profile for inference can also be more flexible than for training. While top-of-the-line GPUs and large, highly clustered machines remain critical for massive model training runs, smaller or older-generation GPUs are often sufficient to run many open-source large language models in production. Kuzco, for example, aggregates capacity from high-performance consumer cards (like RTX 4090s) and idle data center inventory, offering a more cost-effective alternative to single-tenant enterprise GPUs. Solutions like this also highlight another advantage of decentralized platforms: cross-border settlement via stablecoins allows data centers and individual GPU holders around the world to join a single marketplace without being constrained by payment rails. With the cost of inference predicted to grow by orders of magnitude in the coming years, this distributed marketplace approach could become a cornerstone for developers seeking to scale and serve their AI applications sustainably.

Another noteworthy entrant in the inference layer is RedPill, which operates more as a routing and aggregation solution than a raw GPU marketplace. Rather than matching idle GPUs to developer workloads, RedPill focuses on letting developers easily switch between multiple large language models like OpenAI’s GPT-4, Anthropic’s Claude, or Meta’s Llama via a single, unified API. By presenting these models under one umbrella, RedPill streamlines the complexity of juggling multiple accounts or APIs and often provides cost savings through flexible pricing structures. RedPill also uses a token-based system—specifically, $wGPT—as a pre-funded credit mechanism for AI usage. Developers deposit $wGPT to set up their spending limits, enabling them to pay for any supported model’s inference on a pay-as-you-go basis without rigid usage caps. Just as distributed GPU networks aim to drive down the cost of serving inferences, RedPill helps reduce developers’ operational overhead.

Other Notable Categories

While advancements and contributions from decentralized protocols to the AI model workflow are encouraging, they are often mainly focused on cost reductions or improving system fault-tolerance. What about the apps? Among accelerator participants, we noted many projects building in the consumer app and agent categories.

Consumer

  • Sekai lets users create sharable generative AI stories, characters, and artwork.
  • Titles allows artists to monetize their style through models trained on their artwork.
  • Story Chain is also focused on collaborative storytelling through generative AI.
  • NFPrompt streamlines the generative AI to NFT minting process.
  • Searchpad is targeted towards content generation across social media.

Agents

  • LIFT creates agents to turn content (like streaming or video) into data in real-time.
  • PIN AI creates personal AI assistants run locally on devices.
  • Fungi is an agent that can conduct activities across DeFi platforms.
  • Nimble provides an agent development hub for web2 and web3 apps.
  • Skyfire provides a platform for agent payments.
  • Holoworld allows for no-code agent creation with 3d avatars and animation.
  • Scrypted aims to create infrastructure for autonomous agents.

Looking ahead, the convergence of AI research with crypto-based incentives and infrastructure suggests a future where everything from data creation to model deployment can be globally crowdsourced, opening new frontiers for open-source AI progress. Keep an eye on future AI accelerator rounds in our fundraising data to see where the puck is going.
